Answer: The British Royal Family refers to the relatives of the sovereign monarch of the United Kingdom and 14 other Commonwealth realms. The current British sovereign is King Charles III, who ascended to the throne following the death of his mother, Queen Elizabeth II. The late Queen Elizabeth II ruled for over 70 years, making her Britain's longest-reigning monarch.

In 1901, King Edward VII succeeded his mother, Queen Victoria of the House of Hanover, as the new monarch of the United Kingdom, ushering in a new era for the Royal Family. Since Edward VII's reign, there have been five other monarchs in the royal house: George V, Edward VIII, George VI, Elizabeth II, and Charles III.

The House of Windsor is the sovereign monarchy for 15 countries, including the United Kingdom, Canada, Australia, New Zealand, Jamaica, the Bahamas, Grenada, Papua New Guinea, the Solomon Islands, Tuvalu, Saint Lucia, Saint Vincent and the Grenadines, Belize, Antigua and Barbuda, and Saint Kitts and Nevis.

Answer: The House of Windsor is the name of the official ruling family, succeeding the House of Hanover once ruled by Queen Victoria. Originally, the House of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha ruled, but the name was changed under the rule of King George V during World War I to Windsor to avoid anti-German sentiment. Since George V, four other monarchs under the Windsor name have ruled: Edward VIII, George VI, Elizabeth II, and Charles III.

Answer: Overall, the royal family engages in public ceremonies and events, as well as charitable activities. British royals are considered cultural icons and stars in their own right within the UK. Weddings and funerals of close relatives of the monarch have received worldwide attention.
Answer: Active members of the royal family include King Charles III, Queen Camilla, Prince William of Wales, Princess Catherine of Wales, Princess Anne, Prince Edward, and Sophie.
Other members of the royal family who do not hold as senior a rank include Prince Richard, Duke of Gloucester, his wife Birgitte and Princess Alexandra.
The first royal members to succeed the King include Prince William and Prince George of Wales, son of Prince William and Princess Catherine.
Other children of the Prince and Princess of Wales include Princess Charlotte and Prince Louis.

Answer: Prince Harry, Duke of Sussex, the second son of King Charles III and Princess Diana, and his wife Meghan Markle, Duchess of Sussex, left their roles as official senior members of the royal family in March 2020.
The pair uprooted their lives in the UK and moved to Canada before settling in Southern California. They have two children: Prince Archie of Sussex and Princess Lilibet of Sussex.
Harry and Meghan's exit from the royal family, including establishing financial independence from the monarchy, sparked rumors and made headlines.

In 2023, Harry released a memoir titled "Spare," which quickly sold over 6 million copies. In the book, he claimed he and Prince William begged their father not to marry Camilla. King Charles and Camilla were in a relationship for decades, even while Charles was married to the late Princess Diana.
